    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-02-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-02-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="249"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d249">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 GE/2–2354</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Deputy Under Secretary of State for
                        Political Affairs</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MRD1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Murphy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d249fn1">Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_PDH1"
                            >Popper</persName> of <gloss target="#t_UNP1">UNP</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-02-23">February 23,
                            1954</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>Preparations for Geneva Political Conference</item>
                </list>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">Discussion:</hi>
                </p>
                <p>To plan efficiently for the Geneva Conference, I suggest that you designate an
                    officer of the Department to coordinate all preparations. Perhaps <persName
                        corresp="#p_MAD1">Douglas MacArthur</persName> would be the appropriate
                    man.</p>
                <p>I would also recommend that two small task forces be set up for substantive
                    preparations. One, on Korea, might be steered by <gloss target="#t_UNP1"
                        >UNP</gloss>, with <gloss target="#t_NA1">NA</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_CA1"
                        >CA</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_EE1">EE</gloss> participating. The other,
                    on Indo-China, could be steered by <gloss target="#t_PSA1">PSA</gloss>, with
                        <gloss target="#t_CA1">CA</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_WE1">WE</gloss>, <gloss
                        target="#t_EE1">EE</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_UNP1">UNP</gloss>
                    participating.</p>
                <p>The Division of International Conferences will provide the usual administrative
                    support.</p>
                <pb facs="0443" n="417" xml:id="pg_417"/>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">Recommendation:</hi>
                </p>
                <p>That you approve the foregoing designations.<note n="2" xml:id="d249fn2">Approved
                        by the Secretary. Handwritten notation on source text indicated that
                        Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> wanted <persName
                            corresp="#p_YKT1">Kenneth T. Young</persName> of <gloss target="#t_NA1"
                            >NA</gloss> for Korea and for <persName corresp="#p_MAD1"
                            >MacArthur</persName> to pick someone for Indochina with <persName
                            corresp="#p_RWS1">Robertson</persName>’s approval. <persName
                            corresp="#p_BPW1">Philip W. Bonsal</persName> of <gloss target="#t_PSA1"
                            >PSA</gloss> was designated for Indochina (see the memorandum, <ref
                            target="#pg_425">p. 425</ref>).</note>
                </p>
            </div>
